Normative spec for the `.steno` DSL — the source format parsed by `crates/steno/src/parse/` and count-bank logic in `crates/steno/src/stroke/`. This file is documentation only, not code, but it's the authoritative reference other docs and the parser must stay consistent with; the doc explicitly declares that when it and the code disagree, the code wins, so edits here should be checked against the parser rather than treated as ground truth on their own.

Covers four things line-by-line parsers must handle: fenced entries (blocks opened by a line of 4+ backticks plus a non-empty stroke, closed by bare backticks), directives (`@name arg`, attaching to the entry directly above, unknown names being errors), comments (`#` or `//`, only outside fenced blocks — inside a block those characters are literal template text), and template-body operators (`%0`-`%9` landings, `%d` count digit, `%t` type slot, `%b` body break, `%p` pattern, `%[sep|body%]` repeat, `%(EXPR)` computed landing, plus backslash escapes).

Key non-obvious details an editor must get right if changing this doc:
- Stroke canonical key order is `# | S T K P W H R | A O * E U | F R P B L G T S D Z`; the hyphen is used only to separate right-bank keys when no middle key is present — this exact rule governs re-rendering after count-key merge (e.g. `STKWR-PBGS/-FLT` + count 3 → `STKWR-PBGS/AOFLT`).
- `@count KEYS` reads keys **LSB-first** (first listed key = bit 0), and merges bits of the target count into the entry's **last** sub-stroke only; a bank of width `w` covers `0..=2^w-1`, count keys must be middle or right-bank keys, and a key already present in that sub-stroke is an error.
- The seven directives (`@count`, `@arity`, `@multiline`, `@type`, `@noarg`, `@fuse`, `@literal`) each have distinct semantics for the type-append pass and snippet expansion described in `pipeline.md` — `@fuse` in particular changes stroke-count semantics by merging the entry's last stroke into the first appended type stroke.
- `%[sep|body%]` never emits `sep` after the last repeat; `%(EXPR)` is linear in the in-scope count `d`, negative results error, and there's no renumbering (so an unresolved landing collision at expansion time is an error, unlike plain `%0`-`%9` landings which snippets do renumber).
- Errors (stray closing fence, unterminated block, unknown directive, unterminated `%[`/`%(`, unknown `\x` escape, trailing backslash at EOF) all carry source line (and for operator errors, column) — any reference implementation must preserve that error-reporting contract.

Cross-references: `pipeline.md` (Pass A) owns the expansion-time semantics of `%d`/`%[…%]`/`%(…)` against a resolved count value, and the `@literal` directive's block-expansion behavior; `dict.steno`'s header comment and the `parse/` and `stroke/` modules are the actual ground truth this doc summarizes.